      "id": 1,
      "text": "Dayville grew around the Norwich & Worcester railroad station, becoming a shipping point for nearby villages.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        5
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://connecticutgenealogy.com/windham/history_of_dayville_connecticut.htm"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "Captain John Day partnered with Prosper and William Alexander to build a cotton factory in 1832.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        10
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://connecticutgenealogy.com/windham/history_of_dayville_connecticut.htm"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "John Day later erected a brick factory that operated until its destruction in 1858, after which the business was sold.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        11
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://connecticutgenealogy.com/windham/history_of_dayville_connecticut.htm"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Historic Sanborn Fire Insurance Maps from 1892 to 1917 document Dayville’s layout, showing businesses and industrial buildings.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
